<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911212-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>911212-0016.</DOCID><HL>   Politics andamp; Policy:   Teeter to Leave News Polls   To Oversee Bush Campaign</HL><DATE>12/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16</SO><CO>   DJ GE WNEWS</CO><MS>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)PUBLISHING, INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANIES (PUB)</IN><NS>PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)POLITICS (PLT)</NS><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Republican pollster Robert Teeter isstepping aside from his role with The Wall Street Journal/NBCNews poll in light of his appointment to a key job inPresident Bush's re-election campaign.   Mr. Teeter, who since 1989 has conducted the Journal/NBCsurvey in collaboration with Democratic pollster Peter Hart,has been named chairman of the president's re-electioneffort. In that role, he will be the campaign's chiefstrategist and oversee its day-to-day operations.</LP><TEXT>   During Mr. Teeter's absence, his role with the Journal/NBCpoll will be filled by Vince Breglio, a Republican pollsterwho is president of Research/Strategy/ Management Inc., aconsulting firm based here. Mr. Breglio, 51 years old, servedas director of polling for the 1988 Bush-Quayle campaign, andis a former executive director of the National RepublicanSenatorial Committee. He has conducted surveys for a varietyof political and commercial clients.   Mr. Breglio will work on the Journal/NBC poll with Mr.Hart. Neither is working for any presidential candidate in1992.</TEXT></DOC>